title: Add KiCad symbol metadata support to schematic symbols
description: Add support for KiCad symbol metadata in schematic symbols, allowing for structured storage of KiCad-specific information such as pin names, numbers, and properties.
body:
### Motivation
- Provide a structured schema for KiCad symbol metadata so schematic symbols can carry KiCad-specific information (pin names/numbers, properties, effects) and pave the way for future KiCad footprint usage.

### Description
- Add `src/common/kicadSymbolMetadata.ts` containing Zod schemas and TypeScript interfaces for symbol pin numbers, pin names, effects, properties, and top-level symbol metadata with `expectTypesMatch` checks.
- Add `src/common/kicadFootprintMetadata.ts` containing shared KiCad types (`kicadAt`, `kicadFont`, footprint properties, pads, models) for reuse by symbol metadata and future footprint integration.
- Export both new modules from `src/common/index.ts` and extend the `SchematicSymbol` TypeScript interface and Zod schema in `src/schematic/schematic_symbol.ts` to include an optional `kicad_symbol_metadata` field.
- Update `tests/schematic_symbol.test.ts` to include a test asserting that `kicad_symbol_metadata` parses correctly and adjust schema input typing to `z.input` for compatibility.

### Testing
- Ran `bun test tests/schematic_symbol.test.ts` which passed all tests (`3 pass, 0 fail`).
- Ran `bunx tsc --noEmit` for type checking which completed successfully with no errors.
- Ran `bun run format` to apply code formatting successfully.

title: Implement Soldermask Rendering for Top and Bottom Boards using circuit-to-canvas
description: This PR extracts soldermask generation into a dedicated texture pipeline for 3D boards, replacing the previous inline handling inside the combined texture builder. A new createSoldermaskTextureForLayer module renders top and bottom soldermask independently using CircuitToCanvasDrawer, aligned to board outline bounds and material-aware color selection. The implementation ensures accurate compositing by rendering mask layers first and applying uncovered copper pours using destination-out blending, producing clean and deterministic cutouts. Directional control for top and bottom layers is explicit, improving separation between board sides and eliminating ambiguity in mask stacking. createCombinedBoardTextures is simplified by delegating soldermask generation to the new engine, reducing coupling between mask logic and other board textures such as traces, pads, silkscreen, and pours. A comprehensive Storybook fixture validates soldermask margin story behavior across all supported pad, plated hole, and non-plated hole geometries, covering fully covered, positive margin, negative margin, and default scenarios. This establishes a strong visual regression surface for soldermask edge cases. The result is a cleaner architecture, higher rendering determinism, and robust support for complex soldermask margin behavior in the 3D pipeline.
body:
This PR extracts soldermask generation into a dedicated texture pipeline for 3D boards, replacing the previous inline handling inside the combined texture builder. A new createSoldermaskTextureForLayer module renders top and bottom soldermask independently using CircuitToCanvasDrawer, aligned to board outline bounds and material-aware color selection.

The implementation ensures accurate compositing by rendering mask layers first and applying uncovered copper pours using destination-out blending, producing clean and deterministic cutouts. Directional control for top and bottom layers is explicit, improving separation between board sides and eliminating ambiguity in mask stacking.

createCombinedBoardTextures is simplified by delegating soldermask generation to the new engine, reducing coupling between mask logic and other board textures such as traces, pads, silkscreen, and pours.

A comprehensive Storybook fixture validates soldermask margin story behavior across all supported pad, plated hole, and non-plated hole geometries, covering fully covered, positive margin, negative margin, and default scenarios. This establishes a strong visual regression surface for soldermask edge cases.

The result is a cleaner architecture, higher rendering determinism, and robust support for complex soldermask margin behavior in the 3D pipeline.

title: Allow linking org domains to package `latest` (Use Latest Version default)
description: Add a Use Latest Version checkbox to the AddLinkedPackageDialog, enabling users to link to the latest package release by default, while preventing duplicate links for the same package.
body:
### Motivation
- Provide an easy way for org domains to track a packages latest release instead of forcing users to pick a specific release, and make that the default behavior when adding linked packages.
- Ensure the frontend and hooks support creating links that point to a package tag (e.g. `latest`) as well as preventing duplicate "latest" links for the same package.

### Description
- Add a `Use Latest Version` checkbox to `AddLinkedPackageDialog` and make it enabled by default, sending `points_to: "package_release_with_tag"`, `package_id` and `tag: "latest"` when selected, while preserving the existing specific-release flow when unchecked (`src/components/dialogs/add-linked-package-dialog.tsx`).
- Pass `existingLatestPackageIds` from `OrgDomainsList` to the add dialog to disable adding duplicate latest-type links, and show linked package labels as `Package (Latest Version)` when a link points to `package_release_with_tag: latest` (`src/components/org-settings/OrgDomainsList.tsx`).
- Extend the mutation type for adding linked packages to accept both `points_to: "package_release"` and `points_to: "package_release_with_tag"` payloads with optional `package_release_id`, `package_id`, and `tag` fields (`src/hooks/use-org-domains.ts`).

### Testing
- Ran `bunx tsc --noEmit` for type checking, which completed successfully.
- Ran `bun test src/components/dialogs` which returned no matching test files in that directory (no unit tests were found for these components).
- Ran `bun run format` to apply formatting changes successfully.

body:
### Motivation

- Mirror production `filter_preset` behavior in the fake API so front-end code and tests can rely on the same domain selection semantics.
- Ensure `package_id`-scoped presets only work when a `package_id` is provided and include domains that point to a package indirectly via releases or builds.

### Description

- Added `filter_preset` to the route `commonParams` and return a `400` error with `error_code: "missing_parameter"` when `filter_preset` is provided without `package_id`.
- Implemented preset filtering that returns all `package_release_with_tag` domains plus the latest `package_release` and latest `package_build` domains when `filter_preset` is present.
- Enhanced `package_id` filtering to include domains that point to the package indirectly by resolving `package_release_id` and `package_build_id` back to their owning package.
- Added tests in `bun-tests/fake-snippets-api/routes/package_domains/list.test.ts` to validate the preset selection (tagged + latest release/build, excluding package-only domains) and the missing-`package_id` validation.

### Testing

- Ran the focused test file with `bun test bun-tests/fake-snippets-api/routes/package_domains/list.test.ts` and all tests in that file passed.
- Type-checked the project with `bunx tsc --noEmit` which succeeded with no errors.

title: Show all package-linked domains in package settings
description: Adds a new hook to display all fully qualified domain names (FQDNs) linked to a package, including those from releases and builds, in the package settings.
body:
### Motivation
- The Domains tab should display every FQDN linked to a package, including domains attached to the package itself and to any releases or builds for that package.

### Description
- Added a new hook `useAllPackageLinkedDomains(packageId)` in `src/hooks/use-package-domains.ts` that lists package releases and builds, fetches domains for the package, each release, and each build, deduplicates by `package_domain_id`, and sorts results newest-first.
- Updated `PackageDomainsList` (`src/components/package-settings/PackageDomainsList.tsx`) to use `useAllPackageLinkedDomains` and show all linked domains instead of only querying the latest release or the package alone.
- Domain fetching uses parallel requests (`Promise.all`) and a `Map` to de-duplicate entries, preserving existing UI and domain target resolution logic.

### Testing
- Ran type checking with `bun run typecheck` (`tsc --noEmit`) which succeeded.
- Ran formatting with `bunx biome format --write` for modified files which succeeded.
- Started the dev server with `bun run dev --port 4173` and captured a browser screenshot via a Playwright script; the server started but autoload of some dev packages failed due to network fetch errors (these are unrelated to the new hook logic).

title: Use release/build versions in package domain target descriptions
description: Provides clearer, human-readable context for package domains by showing the actual release version or associated release for builds instead of opaque IDs.
body:
### Motivation
- Provide clearer, human-readable context for package domains by showing the actual release version or associated release for builds instead of opaque IDs.
- Address inline review feedback to rename the helper output field from `details` to `description` for clearer semantics.

### Description
- Add and centralize formatting logic in `src/lib/package-domain-target.ts` by introducing `getPackageDomainTargetInfo(domain, context)` which accepts `releaseVersionById` and `buildById` lookup maps and returns `{ badgeLabel, description }`.
- Prefer real release versions (formatted with a `v` prefix) in `package_release` descriptions and include the associated release version when a `package_build` points to a build.
- Wire the package settings UI to fetch releases and builds and pass the context into `getPackageDomainTargetInfo` in `src/components/package-settings/PackageDomainsList.tsx` so list rows and the edit dialog show richer descriptions.
- Update `EditSubdomainDialog` (`src/components/dialogs/edit-subdomain-dialog.tsx`) to accept and render the precomputed `targetInfo` `description` and `badgeLabel`.
- Add unit tests for the helper in `src/lib/package-domain-target.test.ts` covering both `package_release` and `package_build` description behavior.

### Testing

title: Enable Dynamic Board Sizing in FootprintPreview to Prevent Component Overflow
description: Removes fixed width and height properties from the FootprintPreview component to allow dynamic sizing based on component dimensions, preventing overflow issues in multi-footprint previews.
body: This pull request makes a small update to the `FootprintPreview` component by removing the explicit `width` and `height` properties from the `grids` configuration and from the generated `` element. The board is now rendered without fixed width and height values. - Removed the `width` and `height` properties from the `grids` configuration for all grid sizes in `FootprintPreview.tsx` [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-ff47d5285a65fe1dfb15928a82bdbf3549ce3c1a40b45b1527ba862d46219c3fL6-L7) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-ff47d5285a65fe1dfb15928a82bdbf3549ce3c1a40b45b1527ba862d46219c3fL17-L18) [[3]](diffhunk://#diff-ff47d5285a65fe1dfb15928a82bdbf3549ce3c1a40b45b1527ba862d46219c3fL28-L29) - Updated the generated `` element to no longer include `width` and `height` attributes In multi-footprint previews, components like "stampboard", "stampreceiver", and "qfp" were overflowing from the hardcoded small board dimensions (e.g., 30mm 12mm for 2 footprints). This caused visual clipping and potential DRC errors in the PCB view, degrading the user experience when viewing footprint documentation. Solution Modified the FootprintPreview component to omit width and height props from the generated element in multi-footprint mode. This leverages tscircuit's auto-sizing feature, allowing the board to dynamically expand based on the actual footprint sizes and grid positions, ensuring all components fit within the board boundaries. Changes Updated code generation in [FootprintPreview.tsx](vscode-file://vscode-app/opt/visual-studio-code/resources/app/out/vs/code/electron-browser/workbench/workbench.html) to remove hardcoded board dimensions. Retained grid positioning logic for proper component placement. No impact on single-footprint mode, which already uses auto-sizing. Impact Major UX Improvement (2x Multiplier): Significantly enhances the reliability and usability of footprint previews in the documentation site, preventing confusing overflow issues for users exploring footprints. Core Rendering Fix (1.6x Multiplier): Improves how PCBs are rendered in preview contexts, aligning with tscircuit's dynamic layout capabilities. This change ensures footprint previews accurately represent component layouts without arbitrary size constraints, benefiting developers and designers using the tscircuit ecosystem. ## Before ## After

title: fix: use actual RefDes for Reference property in kicad-project output
description: Fixes the Reference property in kicad-project output to use the actual component name from circuit-json instead of a shared metadata value, ensuring unique RefDes for each component.
body:
Reference property: Always uses componentName from circuit-json (e.g., "MC1", "MC2"). Metadata Reference.value is ignored because metadata is shared by prefix and would cause all components to have the same RefDes.

Value property: Uses valMeta?.value if provided, otherwise falls back to metadata.footprintName.

Metadata still controls styling: hide, position, layer, font effects for bothproperties.
